					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    High Elf Wizard Guide: From Bats to Ports</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:fries@hog.net">friday jones</a> | 
		            2/8/2001 8:28:33 AM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">First, create your High Elf Wizard.  You will start out in Felwithe, in Greater Faydark on Faydwer.<BR>
 <BR>
New High Elf Wizards have 25 bonus character points.  I recommend putting the maximum allowed into Intelligence (20 points), and the remainder (5 points) into Dex (weapon procs), Agi (better AC), Str (can carry more), or Cha (buy for less, sell for more to NPC's).<BR>
 <BR>
You will start out in Felwithe city, near the Bank,  Towards the back of the city, by a fishmonger's hut, is a tunnel leading to the Magical Guilds.  The Wizard's Guild is marked by a sign with the same picture as your statistics screen has on it, an upturned hand with smoke rising from the palm.  Your Master is Tarker Blazetoss.  Give him the letter you have in your possession, and he will give you a nifty green robe and two magical spells!  To use these spells, open your spellbook, and pick up the spell scroll from your inventory, and click on an empty slot in your spellbook.  The spell will scribe into the book permanently.  To memorize the spell for use, click on the spell in the book, and then click on an empty spell jewel on the left of your screen.  The spell will memorize.  To cast it you just click on a monster to target it, then click the spell jewel.<BR>
 <BR>
Levels 1-4<BR>
Right outside the gates to the city are two guards.  These guards will kill anything you can't handle, if you run between them.  There is a grassy hill in front of the gates.  This is the center of your activities for the first couple of levels.  Cast your Shield spell.  This will add to your combat abilities.  Then target a bat that is not too close by, and attack it using your Shock of Frost spell.  The bat will get angry an attack you.  Hit your autoattack key (it is &quot;a&quot; by default), and your character will fight the bat with its dagger.  When the bat dies, your health will probably be down a bit, and casting spells reduces your mana.  By waiting near the guards for a bit, your health and mana will rise to normal again.<BR>
 <BR>
Bats are best for first level.  They are not hard to kill, and you will hit 2nd level very soon.  Then you can attack Decaying Skeletons and Black Wolves too.  The bone chips can be turned in 4 at a time in your cleric's guild (the building facing the fishing dock), and if you get a Black Wolf Skin you can give it to Parker Blazetoss and he might give you your first area effect spell, or a rusty dagger or a copper ring.<BR>
 <BR>
Sometime during the 1-4 level period, you will grow bored of the Felwithe newbie area, and all you have to do is take the path to the right, and follow it straight to Kelethin, the Wood Elf city.  Ask around and you can find a caster who can &quot;bind&quot; you (so when you die you appear in Kelethin instead of Felwithe).  The Kelethin newbie area is more lively, and when you hit level 5 you can move on to Orc Hill and fight Orc Centurions.<BR>
 <BR>
At level 4, you MUST train a point into Meditation with Tarker Blazetoss.  From then on, whenever you open your spellbook, you automatically meditate, which returns mana at a much faster rate.  Memming spells is faster too.<BR>
 <BR>
Levels 5-7<BR>
Orc Hill.  This small hill has several Orc camps around it, and it is a great place to group for experience from levels 5-7.  It is near to the entrance to Crushbone, which is one of the places people play from levels 8 all the way to the low 20's sometimes.  To fight on Orc Hill, just group up, and work together.  This is where you learn strategy &quot;hands-on&quot; in a group, and where players first learn to work together with other classes.<BR>
 <BR>
A Wizard on Orc Hill should allow a &quot;Tank&quot; class (maybe a Warrior, Paladin, Shadowknight, Bard, or other armor-wearing class that can melee) to &quot;pull&quot; an orc from one of the camps to where your group is fighting, and when it arrives, let the tank make the monster good and mad at him.  Then, before the tank gets hurt too bad, you start unloading with your best damage spell.  Sometimes the tank will accidentally bring more than one monster (an &quot;overpull&quot; or &quot;add&quot;), and you will want to target the TANK, and type /assist, which will cause you to targer the monster he's already hitting.  Otherwise, you would hit a fresh monster, and it would attack you.  Burn down the first monster, then use /assist again to switch targets until the orcs are all dead.  If the tanks says to run, you RUN to the guards or to the CB zone.<BR>
 <BR>
Levels 8-11<BR>
You can either go into Crushbone now and get into groups, or you can go solo in Butcherblock.  I preferred the BB route, because CB is so rough with the trains in there.  The BB zone is at -1500, 2400.  I like to fight near the zone line, if I am losing I can just run for it back to Gfay.  Look for something that /considers white or blue to you.  You can do this by right-clicking on monsters.  If it cons white or blue, then back away from it to your maximum Fire Bolt distance, and attack with a Fire Bolt.  It will start running towards you.  While it is running, use another Fire Bolt.  By now, it is in range of your Shock of Ice spell (shorter range than Bolt spells).  With two Fire Bolts already, one Shock of Ice will usually cause enough additional damage to cause the monster to turn and start running away.  If it is running fast, another Shock of Ice spell will kill it, if it is running slowly then just stab it in the back until it dies.<BR>
 <BR>
Some people say a Wizard needs to Root and then nuke the monster while it is stuck.  This is not really very useful advice.  Root breaks too easily, it's better to be used on monsters you don't intend to damage for a while.  Using Bolt spells at full range works better at these low levels, and is more mana-efficient.  <BR>
 <BR>
Bring bandages, when you do wind up taking damage, you can speed up the healing process by badaging yourself up to 50% of your maximum health.  A good bandaging skill makes soloing more efficient.<BR>
 <BR>
Levels 12-15<BR>
Again, a choice between soloing and grouping is available.  Grouping can be done in these levels in North Ro, ButcherBlock Mountains, Steamfont's Mino Caves, Crushbone, and many other places.  To solo, I recomment the Steamfont Mountains, just outside the Mino Caves.  There you will find a lot of randomly-spawning wandering monsters, including Harpys (my favorite), Lesser Ebon Drakes, Earth and Steam Elementals, Rogue Clockworks, and Giant Diseased/Plague Rats, and even Minotaurs.<BR>
 <BR>
Use /con to only attack blues and whites.  Use the Bolt/Bolt/Shock method I described above, only with better spells now that you're 12th and up.  Do not attack the Rats or the Clockworks.  The Rats, Minos, and Elementals are agro on Wizards.  Try to choose a fighting place where they are not currently wandering through.  I like to &quot;pull&quot; to the hillside, which has no wanderers.  The Clockworks are cooperative, so if you attack one, another might attack.  I preferred Harpys and Lesser Ebon Drakes, because they are non-agro, non-cooperative, and give good XP at the level.  They both have identical AoE breath weapons, so careful not to let your Drake or Harpy agro a different mob, you might lose the XP to another monster.<BR>
 <BR>
If you hit a harpy with a Bolt spell, she will come after you.  Fire a second Bolt spell, and then start a Shock of Lightning spell.  The Harpy will stop to cast her breath weapon on you as soon as she's in range.  It doesn't really hurt much though.  But she stops long enough usually to get that Shock spell off.  Then melee with her.  She won't be as easy to &quot;turn&quot; as the monsters were at level 8, so you have to melee a bit, but it's no worse than when you used to fight bats.<BR>
 <BR>
Level 16-19<BR>
Again, a choice between grouping and soloing.  To group, just go to the Estate of Unrest and get a group.  This is another dungeon type setting like Crushbone, with even worse trains, but decent loot drops here.  The soloing option is to go to the Oasis of Marr.<BR>
 <BR>
Take the boat from Butcherblock to Freeport, and then go out the South Gate, zone into North Ro, and run leftwards to the coast.  Follow the coast southwards until you zone into the Oasis of Marr.  Bind yourself on the beach on the North Ro side of the zone.  Your sitting and meditating spot (while soloing) is on the Oasis side of the zone, right next to the water and the zone line.<BR>
 <BR>
Always meditate to full mana and health before looking for a fight.  Never stray too far from the beach.  If you wander south too far, you will find the Docks.  This is a dangerous place, because idiots train Sand Giants and Spectres there, and they will kill you fast.<BR>
 <BR>
With a full load of mana and a full healthbar, it's time to hunt.  I recommend using headphones to track monsters by sound.  Otherwise the rolling sand dunes hide a lot of XP.  I wander slowly south from the zone line along the beach, listening for a growling sound that crocodilians make.  When I hear it, I turn until my stereo headphones tell me I'm pointing right at the monster.  I run towards it until I see it.<BR>
 <BR>
Then I /con the monster.  Caimins tend to be the lowest level crocodilians in Oasis, with Crocodiles, then Deepwater Caimins, and finally Deepwater Crocodiles, each being progressivley higher level on average.  Only attack BLUE conning crocs and caimins, and even if it cons blue, the Deepwater Crocs bite too hard to fight safely.  Stick to the other three types.  Watch out for a named Croc called Lockjaw, not agro but deadly.<BR>
 <BR>
To fight the Crocs, I started out (when I was 16th and had a smaller mana pool) using Bolt/Bolt/Shock, then meleeing, much as in Steamfont.  These guys are tougher than Harpys, so you WILL take a LOT more damage.  Bandaging is essential soloing in Oasis.<BR>
 <BR>
When you hit level 18, and you are focusing only on Crocs and Deepwater Caimins (which bite hard and have lots of hit points), you will finally need to try to Root kite.  Bolt first, then Root while it's running towards you.  Move to maximum Shock spell range, then use Shock of Lightning until Root breaks, re-Root, back up, and repeat.  When you get the monster below 30%, stop Rooting it because you want it to run while you stab it in the back.<BR>
 <BR>
Level 20 and Beyond<BR>
Okay, you have reached level 20.  If you have gotten this far, you probably don't NEED a Strategy Guide to continue, you have friends and a general knowledge of the game now.  I recommend fighting for the next few levels in South Karana and Lake Rathetear, and ONLY in groups.  If you solo too much, you won't have the network of friends that makes this game playable in the high end.  You also need to learn how to work in a group at the high end, how Agro works, what Enchanters can do now, all that will require grouping.<BR>
 <BR>
I recommend getting into an XP group in SK (like at the Aviaks), sit down, med, keep your ears open and your mouth shut, and do EXACTLY AS YOU'RE TOLD.  If you play your cards right, you will learn a lot, and make some tight friends.  Once you hit level 29, the money will roll in, so don't be a Greedy Gus when it comes to looting.  Try to make friends, or this game will bore you to death.<BR>
 <BR>
Equipment<BR>
I recommend sticking with the Piercing weapons (pun intended).  It seems great, the damage that a Cracked Staff can deliver, and there are relatively inexpensive Magical Staves (like the Water Crystal Staff or the Staff of Writhing) that have even better damage, and will even process a magic spell if the wielder is above a certain level.  But Staves are SLOW.  You only get skill increases for each attack, so if you get more attacks per second, you get more practice too.  So blunt weapons hit hard, but slow, and take a lot of swinging to improve.  A Dragoon Dirk has the same attack rating as a Staff of Writhing.  The Staff will do maybe 18-19 in a HIE Wizard's hands, the Dirk will do maybe 12-13.  But the Dirk will swing almost twice as many times in a fight, so your skill level increases nearly twice as fast in Piercing.  Also, when you hit level 28, the Staff processes a 48DD spell, which sounds great, but it aggravates the monsters a lot, and that makes it more of a Necro weapon (they will use it on a Feared monster most likely).  The Dragoon Dirk does straight melee damage, with a low taunt factor compared to many DD spells.<BR>
 <BR>
INT items are always good.  In the first 20 levels, Mana items are even more important.  A Skull of Jen'tra is good and cheap, and jaded gold bracelets are good too.  When you get into your teens, you will want to up your INT, so Silver Star Rose Quartz Engagement Rings are good, Blackened Iron Medallions, Polished Bone Bracelets, Savant's Cap, Golden Ear Studs, all are good for adding a few points of INT.  The higher your INT at 20, the better.<BR>
 <BR>
Don't blow your money on a Robe until you can afford one with INT and Mana.  If you are sick of wearing the same robe all the time, go to Erudin and buy a different colored Sr. Apprentice Robe there, or pick up a Gossamer Robe cheap.  Save your money to buy at LEAST a Robe of the Oracle if you are planning on spending the money to buy a decent robe.<BR>
 <BR>
When you hit 29 or so, you will be dying to get a Staff of Temperate Flux.  If you made friends like you should have, you should be able to get one by level 34.  This will help you reduce resistances to Fire and Ice spells, and also acts as a range finder for DD spells when kiting.  This quest is given in the Temple of Solusek.<BR>
 <BR>
While I've only ever seen them on other players, J-Boots are renowned as one of the most desirable pieces of equipment that a Wizard can own.  They are a right-clickable manaless running-speed booster.<BR>
 <BR>
Good luck, and may your enemies only find peace in death, fellow Wizards!<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
